# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In mathematical analysis, **asymptotic analysis**, also known as **asymptotics**, is the development and application of methods that generate an approximate analytical solution to a mathematical problem when a variable or parameter assumes a value that is large, small or near a specified value.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] An example of asymptotic analysis is function approximation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] For example, the function ${\textstyle {\widetilde {y}}(x)=x}$ accurately approximates the function ${\textstyle y(x)=x+e^{-x}}$ for large positive ${\textstyle x}$ values (Figure 1).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] For any desired accuracy, there is a corresponding range of ${\textstyle x}$ values where this accuracy occurs.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In this case, a chosen accuracy with a relative error of less than 1% occurs when the ${\textstyle x}$ values are greater than 3.4.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The prime number theorem is an example of an important asymptotic result.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] For any real number ${\textstyle x}$ , the prime counting function, denoted as ${\textstyle \operatorname {\pi } (x)}$ , is the number of prime numbers less than or equal to ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The function, ${\textstyle x/\ln(x)}$ , approximates the prime counting function for large numbers ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] As in the preceding example, as the number ${\textstyle x}$ becomes increasingly larger, the approximating function becomes increasingly more accurate, leading to an increasingly smaller relative error.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic analysis impacts on many areas of mathematics.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Mathematicians use asymptotic analysis for computing function approximations, implicit functions, integrals, iterated functions, series summation, partial sums, solutions of difference equations. solutions of differential equations and properties of computer algorithms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The relation is an equivalence relation on the set of functions of x; the functions f and g are said to be *asymptotically equivalent*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The domain of f and g can be any set for which the limit is defined: e.g. real numbers, complex numbers, positive integers.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The same notation is also used for other ways of passing to a limit: e.g.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The way of passing to the limit is often not stated explicitly, if it is clear from the context.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Although the above definition is common in the literature, it is problematic if *g*(*x*) is zero infinitely often as x goes to the limiting value.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] For that reason, some authors use an alternative definition.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] This definition is equivalent to the prior definition if *g*(*x*) is not zero in some neighbourhood of the limiting value.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The zero function, ${\textstyle f(z)=0}$ , can never be equivalent to any other function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The little-o relation has the *partial ordering property* defined as if ${\textstyle f(x)=o(g(x))}$ and ${\textstyle g(x)=o(h(x))}$ then ${\textstyle f(x)=o(h(x))}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic equivalence has reflexive,symmetric and transitive properties.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotically equivalent functions remain asymptotically equivalent under integration if requirements related to convergence are met.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] There are more stringent requirements for asymptotically equivalent functions to remain asymptotically equivalent under differentiation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] An asymptotic expansion of a function *f*(*x*) is in practice an expression of that function in terms of a series, the partial sums of which do not necessarily converge, but such that taking any initial partial sum provides an asymptotic formula for f.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The idea is that successive terms provide an increasingly accurate description of the order of growth of f.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The relation $f-g_{1}-\cdots -g_{k-1}\sim g_{k}$ takes its full meaning if $g_{k+1}=o(g_{k})$ for all *k*, which means the $g_{k}$ form an asymptotic scale.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In that case, some authors may abusively write $f\sim g_{1}+\cdots +g_{k}$ to denote the statement $f-(g_{1}+\cdots +g_{k})=o(g_{k}).$ One should however be careful that this is not a standard use of the $\sim$ symbol, and that it does not correspond to the definition given in § Definition.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In case the asymptotic expansion does not converge, for any particular value of the argument there will be a particular partial sum which provides the best approximation and adding additional terms will decrease the accuracy.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] This optimal partial sum will usually have more terms as the argument approaches the limit value.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic expansions often occur when an ordinary series is used in a formal expression that forces the taking of values outside of its domain of convergence.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The expression on the left is valid on the entire complex plane $w\neq 1$ , while the right hand side converges only for $|w|<1$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The integral on the left hand side can be expressed in terms of the exponential integral.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The integral on the right hand side, after the substitution $u=w/t$ , may be recognized as the gamma function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Here, the right hand side is clearly not convergent for any non-zero value of *t*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] However, by keeping *t* small, and truncating the series on the right to a finite number of terms, one may obtain a fairly good approximation to the value of $\operatorname {Ei} (1/t)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Substituting $x=-1/t$ and noting that $\operatorname {Ei} (x)=-E_{1}(-x)$ results in the asymptotic expansion given earlier in this article.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In mathematical statistics, an asymptotic distribution is a hypothetical distribution that is in a sense the "limiting" distribution of a sequence of distributions.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] A distribution is an ordered set of random variables *Z**i* for *i* = 1, …, *n*, for some positive integer *n*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] An asymptotic distribution allows *i* to range without bound, that is, *n* is infinite.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] A special case of an asymptotic distribution is when the late entries go to zero—that is, the *Z**i* go to 0 as *i* goes to infinity.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Some instances of "asymptotic distribution" refer only to this special case.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] An asymptote is a straight line that a curve approaches but never meets or crosses.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Informally, one may speak of the curve meeting the asymptote "at infinity" although this is not a precise definition.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In the equation $y={\frac {1}{x}},$ *y* becomes arbitrarily small in magnitude as *x* increases.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic analysis is used in several mathematical sciences.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In statistics, asymptotic theory provides limiting approximations of the probability distribution of sample statistics, such as the likelihood ratio statistic and the expected value of the deviance.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic theory does not provide a method of evaluating the finite-sample distributions of sample statistics, however.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Non-asymptotic bounds are provided by methods of approximation theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Examples of applications are the following.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic analysis is a key tool for exploring the ordinary and partial differential equations which arise in the mathematical modelling of real-world phenomena.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] An illustrative example is the derivation of the boundary layer equations from the full Navier-Stokes equations governing fluid flow.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] In many cases, the asymptotic expansion is in power of a small parameter, ε: in the boundary layer case, this is the nondimensional ratio of the boundary layer thickness to a typical length scale of the problem.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Indeed, applications of asymptotic analysis in mathematical modelling often center around a nondimensional parameter which has been shown, or assumed, to be small through a consideration of the scales of the problem at hand.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] Asymptotic expansions typically arise in the approximation of certain integrals (Laplace's method, saddle-point method, method of steepest descent) or in the approximation of probability distributions (Edgeworth series).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] The Feynman graphs in quantum field theory are another example of asymptotic expansions which often do not converge.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-analysis] De Bruijn illustrates the use of asymptotics in the following dialog between Dr.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Investigations by Dingle (1973) revealed that the divergent part of an asymptotic expansion is latently meaningful, i.e. contains information about the exact value of the expanded function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Poincaré and Stieltjes independently developed the theory of asymptotic expansions in 1886.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The most common type of asymptotic expansion is a power series in either positive or negative powers.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Methods of generating such expansions include the Euler–Maclaurin summation formula and integral transforms such as the Laplace and Mellin transforms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Repeated integration by parts will often lead to an asymptotic expansion.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Since a *convergent* Taylor series fits the definition of asymptotic expansion as well, the phrase "asymptotic series" usually implies a *non-convergent* series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Despite non-convergence, the asymptotic expansion is useful when truncated to a finite number of terms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The approximation may provide benefits by being more mathematically tractable than the function being expanded, or by an increase in the speed of computation of the expanded function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Typically, the best approximation is given when the series is truncated at the smallest term.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] This way of optimally truncating an asymptotic expansion is known as **superasymptotics**.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The error is then typically of the form ~ exp(−*c*/*ε*) where *ε* is the expansion parameter.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The error is thus beyond all orders in the expansion parameter.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] It is possible to improve on the superasymptotic error, e.g. by employing resummation methods such as Borel resummation to the divergent tail.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Such methods are often referred to as **hyperasymptotic approximations**.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] See asymptotic analysis and big O notation for the notation used in this article.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] First we define an asymptotic scale, and then give the formal definition of an asymptotic expansion.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Commonly, L is taken to be zero or infinity.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] In other words, a sequence of functions is an asymptotic scale if each function in the sequence grows strictly slower (in the limit ⁠ $x\to L$ ⁠) than the preceding function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] In contrast to a convergent series for ⁠ f ⁠, wherein the series converges for any *fixed* x in the limit ⁠ $N\to \infty$ ⁠, one can think of the asymptotic series as converging for *fixed* N in the limit $x\to L$ (with L possibly infinite).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The expression on the left is valid on the entire complex plane $w\neq 1$ , while the right hand side converges only for ⁠ $\vert w\vert <1$ ⁠.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] after the substitution $u=w/t$ on the right hand side.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The integral on the left hand side, understood as a Cauchy principal value, can be expressed in terms of the exponential integral.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The integral on the right hand side may be recognized as the gamma function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] However, by truncating the series on the right to a finite number of terms, one may obtain a fairly good approximation to the value of $\operatorname {Ei} \left({\tfrac {1}{t}}\right)$ for sufficiently small *t*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] Substituting $x=-{\tfrac {1}{t}}$ and noting that $\operatorname {Ei} (x)=-E_{1}(-x)$ results in the asymptotic expansion given earlier in this article.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] The minimum occurs at ⁠ $n\sim \vert z\vert$ ⁠, at which point $\textstyle \vert e_{n}(z)\vert \leq {\sqrt {\frac {2\pi }{\vert z\vert }}}e^{-\vert z\vert }$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] This bound is said to be "asymptotics beyond all orders".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] For a given asymptotic scale $\{\varphi _{n}(x)\}$ the asymptotic expansion of function $f(x)$ is unique.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] A given function $f(x)$ may have many asymptotic expansions (each with a different asymptotic scale).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/asymptotic-expansion] An asymptotic expansion may be an asymptotic expansion to more than one function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In computer science, big O notation is used to classify algorithms by how their run time or space requirements grow with the input.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In analytic number theory, big O notation expresses bounds on the growth of an arithmetical function, as for the remainder term in the prime number theorem.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In mathematical analysis, including calculus, Big O notation bounds the error when truncating a power series and expresses the quality of approximation of a real or complex valued function by a simpler function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Often, big O notation characterizes functions according to their growth rates as the variable becomes large: different functions with the same asymptotic growth rate may be represented using the same O notation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The letter O is used because the growth rate of a function is also referred to as the **order of the function**.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] A description of a function in terms of big O notation only provides an upper bound on the growth rate of the function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Associated with big O notation are several related notations, using the symbols o , $\sim$ , $\Omega$ , $\ll$ , $\gg$ , $\asymp$ , $\omega$ , and $\Theta$ to describe other kinds of bounds on growth rates.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Bachmann proposed the notation in 1894 and Landau extended it in 1909.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] An earlier notation was proposed by Paul du Bois-Reymond in 1870.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In most applications, one chooses the function $g(x)$ appearing within the argument of ${\textstyle O{\bigl (}\cdot {\bigr )}}$ to be as simple a form as possible, omitting constant factors and lower order terms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The number ${\textstyle M}$ is called the *implied constant* because it is normally not specified.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] When using big ${\textstyle O}$ notation, what matters is that some finite M exists, not its specific value.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This simplifies the presentation of many analytic inequalities.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For functions defined on positive real numbers or positive integers, a more restrictive and somewhat conflicting definition is still in common use, especially in computer science.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In the 1930s, the Russian number theorist I.M.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Vinogradov introduced the notation $\ll ,$ which has been increasingly used in number theory and other branches of mathematics, as an alternative to the ${\textstyle O}$ notation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Frequently both notations are used in the same work.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In computer science it is common to define big ${\textstyle O}$ as also defining a set of functions.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In typical usage the O notation is applied to an infinite interval of real numbers $[a,\infty )$ and captures the behavior of the function for very large x .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In this setting, the contribution of the terms that grow "most quickly" will eventually make the other ones irrelevant.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For example, let $f(x)=6x^{4}-2x^{3}+5$ , and suppose we wish to simplify this function, using O notation, to describe its growth rate for large x .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Of these three terms, the one with the highest growth rate is the one with the largest exponent as a function of x , namely $6x^{4}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Now one may apply the second rule: $6x^{4}$ is a product of 6 and $x^{4}$ in which the first factor does not depend on x .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Omitting this factor results in the simplified form $x^{4}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Thus, we say that $f(x)$ is a "big O" of $x^{4}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Mathematically, we can write $f(x)=O(x^{4})$ for all $x\geq 1$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] One may confirm this calculation using the formal definition: let $f(x)=6x^{4}-2x^{3}+5$ and $g(x)=x^{4}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Applying the formal definition from above, the statement that $f(x)=O(x^{4})$ is equivalent to its expansion, $|f(x)|\leq Mx^{4}$ for some suitable choice of a positive real number M and for all $x\geq 1$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] On the other hand, the statement $f(x)=O(x^{3})$ is false, because the term $6x^{4}$ causes $f(x)/x^{3}$ to be unbounded.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] When a function $T(n)$ describes the number of steps required in an algorithm with input n , an expression such as $T(n)=O(n^{2})$ with the implied domain being the set of positive integers, may be interpreted as saying that the algorithm has *at most the order of $n^{2}$* time complexity.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Big O can also be used to describe the error term in an approximation to a mathematical function on a finite interval.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The most significant terms are written explicitly, and then the least-significant terms are summarized in a single big O term.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This is an example of the use of Taylor's theorem.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Here we have a complex variable function of two variables.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In general, any bounded function is $O(1)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The last example illustrates a mixing of finite and infinite domains on the different variables.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In all of these examples, the bound is uniform in both variables.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Sometimes in a multivariate expression, one variable is more important than others, and one may express that the implied constant M depends on one or more of the variables using subscripts to the big O symbol or the $\ll$ symbol.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This means that for each real number b , there is a constant $M_{b}$ , *which depends on b*, so that for all $0\leq x\leq 1$ , $|(1+x)^{b}-1|\leq M_{b}\cdot x.$ This particular statement follows from the general binomial theorem.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Another example, common in the theory of Taylor series, is $e^{x}=1+x+O_{r}(x^{2})\quad {\text{ for all }}|x|\leq r,r{\text{ being any real number.}}$ Here the implied constant depends on the size of the domain.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The subscript convention applies to all of the other notations in this page.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] If the function f of a positive integer n can be written as a finite sum of other functions, then the fastest growing one determines the order of $f(n)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For any positive $a,b,$ $(\log n)^{a}=O_{a,b}(n^{b}),$ no matter how large a is and how small b is.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Here, the implied constant depends on both a and b .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For any positive $a,b,$ $n^{a}=O_{a,b}(e^{bn}),$ no matter how large a is and how small b is.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] A function that grows faster than $n^{c}$ for any c is called *superpolynomial*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] One that grows more slowly than any exponential function of the form $c^{n}$ with $c>1$ is called *subexponential*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] An algorithm can require time that is both superpolynomial and subexponential; examples of this include the fastest known algorithms for integer factorization and the function $n^{\log n}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] We may ignore any powers of n inside of the logarithms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For any positive c , the notation $O(\log n)$ means exactly the same thing as $O(\log(n^{c}))$ , since $\log(n^{c})=c\log n$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Similarly, logs with different constant bases are equivalent with respect to Big O notation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] On the other hand, exponentials with different bases are not of the same order.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For example, $2^{n}$ and $3^{n}$ are not of the same order.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In more complicated usage, $O(\cdot )$ can appear in different places in an equation, even several times on each side.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For example, the third equation above means: "For any function satisfying $f(n)=O(1)$ , there is some function $g(n)=O(e^{n})$ such that $n^{f(n)}=g(n)$ ".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The implied constant in the statement " $g(n)=O(e^{n})$ " may depend on the implied constant in the expression " $f(n)=O(1)$ ".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] When $f,g$ are both positive functions, Vinogradov introduced the notation $f(x)\gg g(x)$ , which means the same as $g(x)=O(f(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] which has the same meaning as Vinogradov's $f(x)\gg g(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] However, much earlier, Hardy and Littlewood had defined $\Omega$ differently, and their notation enjoys widespread use today in analytic number theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Justifying his use of the $\Omega$ -symbol to describe a stronger property, Knuth wrote: "For all the applications I have seen so far in computer science, a stronger requirement ... is much more appropriate".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In analytic number theory, the notation $f(x)\asymp g(x)$ means both $f(x)=O(g(x))$ and $g(x)=O(f(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This notation is originally due to Hardy.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Knuth's notation for the same notion is $f(x)=\Theta (g(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Roughly speaking, these statements assert that $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ have the *same order*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] These notations mean that there are positive constants $M,N$ so that $Ng(x)\leq f(x)\leq Mg(x)$ for all x in the common domain of $f,g$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] When the functions are defined on the positive integers or positive real numbers, as with big O, writers oftentimes interpret statements $f(x)=\Omega (g(x))$ and $f(x)=\Theta (g(x))$ as holding for all sufficiently large x , that is, for all x beyond some point $x_{0}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Sometimes this is indicated by appending *$x\to \infty$* to the statement.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For example, $2n^{2}-10n=\Theta (n^{2})$ is true for the domain $n\geq 6$ but false if the domain is all positive integers, since the function is zero at $n=5$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] $f(n)=e^{\Omega (n)}\quad {\text{ for all }}n\geq 1,$ means that there is a positive constant M so that $f(n)\geq e^{Mn}$ for all $n\geq 1$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For any domain D , $f(x)=g(x)+O(1)\Longleftrightarrow e^{f(x)}\asymp e^{g(x)},$ each statement being for all x in D .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Here is a list of classes of functions that are commonly encountered when analyzing the running time of an algorithm.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In each case, *c* is a positive constant and *n* increases without bound.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The slower-growing functions are generally listed first.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The statement $f(n)=O(n!)$ is sometimes weakened to $f(n)=O\left(n^{n}\right)$ to derive simpler formulas for asymptotic complexity.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In many of these examples, the running time is actually $\Theta (g(n))$ , which conveys more precision.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Intuitively, this means that $g(x)$ grows much faster than $f(x)$ , or equivalently $f(x)$ grows much slower than $g(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Little-o respects a number of arithmetic operations.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This definition is especially useful in the computation of limits using Taylor series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] A relation related to little-o is the *asymptotic* notation $\sim$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For real valued functions $f,g$ , the expression $f(x)\sim g(x)\quad {\text{ as }}x\to \infty$ means $\lim _{x\to \infty }{\frac {f(x)}{g(x)}}=1.$ One can connect this to little-o by observing that $f(x)\sim g(x)$ is also equivalent to $f(x)=(1+o(1))g(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Here $o(1)$ refers to a function tending to zero as $x\to \infty$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] One reads this as " $f(x)$ is *asymptotic to* $g(x)$ ".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For nonzero functions on the same (finite or infinite) domain, $\sim$ forms an equivalence relation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For eventually positive, real valued functions $f,g,$ the notation $f(x)=\omega (g(x))\quad {\text{ as }}x\to \infty$ means $\lim _{x\to \infty }{\frac {f(x)}{g(x)}}=\infty .$ In other words, $g(x)=o(f(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Roughly speaking, this means that $f(x)$ grows much faster than does $g(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Landau, with the same meanings, in 1924.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For understanding the formal definitions, consult the list of logic symbols used in mathematics.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The limit definitions assume $g(n)>0$ for n in a neighborhood of the limit; when the limit is $\infty$ , this means that $g(n)>0$ for sufficiently large n .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Computer science and combinatorics use the big O , big Theta $\Theta$ , little o , little omega $\omega$ and Knuth's big Omega $\Omega$ notations.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Analytic number theory often uses the big O , small o , Hardy's $\asymp$ , Hardy–Littlewood's big Omega $\Omega$ (with or without the +, − or ± subscripts), Vinogradov's $\ll$ and $\gg$ notations and $\sim$ notations.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The small omega $\omega$ notation is not used as often in analysis or in number theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Informally, especially in computer science, the big O notation often can be used somewhat differently to describe an asymptotic tight bound where using big Theta $\Theta$ notation might be more factually appropriate in a given context .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For example, when considering a function $T(n)=73n^{3}+22n^{2}+58$ , all of the following are generally acceptable, but tighter bounds (such as numbers 2,3 and 4 below) are usually strongly preferred over looser bounds (such as number 1 below).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] While all three statements are true, progressively more information is contained in each.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In some fields, however, the big O notation (number 2 in the lists above) would be used more commonly than the big Theta notation (items numbered 3 in the lists above).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Another notation sometimes used in computer science is ${\tilde {O}}$ (read *soft-O*), which hides polylogarithmic factors.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] There are two definitions in use: some authors use $f(n)={\tilde {O}}(g(n))$ as shorthand for $f(n)=O(g(n)\log ^{k}n)$ for some k , while others use it as shorthand for $f(n)=O(g(n)\log ^{k}g(n))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] When $g(n)$ is polynomial in n , there is no difference; however, the latter definition allows one to say, e.g. that $n2^{n}={\tilde {O}}(2^{n})$ while the former definition allows for $\log ^{k}n={\tilde {O}}(1)$ for any constant k .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Some authors write *O** for the same purpose as the latter definition.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Essentially, it is less precise version of the big *O* notation, ignoring logarithmic factors in the growth-rate of the function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Since $\log ^{k}n=o(n^{\varepsilon })$ for any constant k and any $\varepsilon >0$ , logarithmic factors are far less significant than powers of n and even more insignificant compared with exponentials.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] is convenient for functions that are between polynomial and exponential in terms of $\log n$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The generalization to functions taking values in any normed vector space is straightforward (replacing absolute values by norms), where f and g need not take their values in the same space.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] A generalization to functions g taking values in any topological group is also possible.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The "limiting process" $x\to x_{0}$ can also be generalized by introducing an arbitrary filter base, i.e. to directed nets f and g .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] which is an equivalence relation and a more restrictive notion than the relationship " f is $\Theta (g)$ " from above.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] (It reduces to $\lim f/g=1$ if f and g are positive real valued functions.) For example, $2x=\Theta (x)$ is, but $2x-x\neq o(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The first and third are symmetric: $f(x)\prec \phi (x)$ means the same as $\phi (x)\succ f(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Landau later adopted $\sim$ with the narrower definition that the limit of $f(x)/\phi (x)$ equals 1.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The symbol O was first introduced by the number theorist Paul Bachmann in 1894, in the second volume of his book *Analytische Zahlentheorie* ("analytic number theory").
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The number theorist Edmund Landau adopted it, and was thus inspired to introduce in 1909 the notation o; hence both are now called Landau symbols.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] These notations were used in applied mathematics during the 1950s for asymptotic analysis.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The symbol $\Omega$ (in the sense "is not little *o* of") was introduced in 1914 by Hardy and Littlewood.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Hardy and Littlewood also introduced in 1916 the left and right $\Omega$ symbols $\Omega _{R}$ , $\Omega _{L}$ (now commonly denoted $\Omega _{+},\Omega _{-}$ ).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This $\Omega$ notation has been commonly used in number theory since the 1950s.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Hardy introduced the symbols $\preccurlyeq$ and advocated for Bois-Reymond's $\prec$ (as well as the already mentioned other symbols) in his 1910 tract "Orders of Infinity", but made use of them only in three papers (1910–1913).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In his nearly 400 remaining papers and books he consistently used the Landau symbols O and o.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The symbol $\sim$ , although it had been used before with different meanings, was given its modern definition by Landau in 1909 and by Hardy in 1910.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] On the same page, Hardy defined the symbol $\asymp$ , where $f(x)\asymp g(x)$ means that both $f(x)=O(g(x))$ and $g(x)=O(f(x))$ are satisfied.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The notation is still used in analytic number theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In the 1930s, Vinogradov popularized the notation $f(x)\ll g(x)$ and $g(x)\gg f(x)$ , both of which mean $f(x)=O(g(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] This notation became standard in analytic number theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In the 1970s, big O was popularized in computer science by Donald Knuth, who proposed the different notation $f(x)=\Theta (g(x))$ for Hardy's $f(x)\asymp g(x)$ , and proposed a different definition for the Hardy and Littlewood Omega notation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In mathematics, an expression such as $x\to \infty$ indicates the presence of a limit.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In big-O notation and related notations $\Omega ,\Theta ,\gg ,\ll ,\asymp$ , there is no implied limit, in contrast with little-o, $\sim$ and $\omega$ notations.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Notation such as $f(x)=O(g(x))\;\;(x\to \infty )$ can be considered an abuse of notation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Some consider $f(x)=O(g(x))$ to also be an abuse of notation, since the use of the equals sign could be misleading as it suggests a symmetry that this statement does not have.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Knuth describes such statements as "one-way equalities", since if the sides could be reversed, "we could deduce ridiculous things like $n=n^{2}$ from the identities $n=O(n^{2})$ and $n^{2}=O(n^{2})$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] For these reasons, some advocate for using set notation and write $f(x)\in O(g(x))$ , read as " $f(x)$ is an element of $O(g(x))$ ", or " $f(x)$ is in the set $O(g(x))$ " – thinking of $O(g(x))$ as the class of all functions $h(x)$ such that $h(x)=O(g(x))$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The Vinogradov notations $\ll$ and $\gg$ , which are widely used in number theory do not suffer from this defect, as they more clearly indicate that big-O indicates an *inequality* rather than an *equality*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] They also enjoy a symmetry that big-O notation lacks: $f(x)\ll g(x)$ means the same as $g(x)\gg f(x)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In combinatorics and computer science, these notations are rarely seen.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Big O is typeset as an italicized uppercase "O", as in the following example: $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] In TeX, it is produced by simply typing 'O' inside math mode.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Unlike Greek-named Bachmann–Landau notations, it needs no special symbol.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] However, some authors use the calligraphic variant ${\mathcal {O}}$ instead.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The big-O originally stands for "order of" ("Ordnung", Bachmann 1894), and is thus a Latin letter.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] Neither Bachmann nor Landau ever call it "Omicron".
[src:asymptotic-analysis/big-o-notation] The symbol was much later on (1976) viewed by Knuth as a capital omicron, probably in reference to his definition of the symbol Omega.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] In mathematics, **Borel summation** is a summation method for divergent series, introduced by Émile Borel (1899).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] It is particularly useful for summing divergent asymptotic series, and in some sense gives the best possible sum for such series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] There are several variations of this method that are also called Borel summation, and a generalization of it called Mittag-Leffler summation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] There are (at least) three slightly different methods called Borel summation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] They differ in which series they can sum, but are consistent, meaning that if two of the methods sum the same series they give the same answer.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] If this converges at *z* ∈ **C** to some function *a*(*z*), we say that the weak Borel sum of *A* converges at *z*, and write ${\textstyle \sum }a_{k}z^{k}=a(z)\,({\boldsymbol {wB}})$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] representing Laplace transform of ${\mathcal {B}}A(z)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] If the integral converges at *z* ∈ **C** to some *a*(*z*), we say that the Borel sum of *A* converges at *z*, and write ${\textstyle \sum }a_{k}z^{k}=a(z)\,({\boldsymbol {B}})$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] This is similar to Borel's integral summation method, except that the Borel transform need not converge for all *t*, but converges to an analytic function of *t* near 0 that can be analytically continued along the positive real axis.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The methods (**B**) and (**wB**) are both regular summation methods, meaning that whenever *A*(*z*) converges (in the standard sense), then the Borel sum and weak Borel sum also converge, and do so to the same value. i.e.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] where the rightmost expression is exactly the Borel sum at *z*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Regularity of (**B**) and (**wB**) imply that these methods provide analytic extensions to *A*(*z*).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Any series *A*(*z*) that is weak Borel summable at *z* ∈ *C* is also Borel summable at *z*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] However, one can construct examples of series which are divergent under weak Borel summation, but which are Borel summable.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The following theorem characterises the equivalence of the two methods.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] There are always many different functions with any given asymptotic expansion.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] However, there is sometimes a best possible function, in the sense that the errors in the finite-dimensional approximations are as small as possible in some region.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Watson's theorem and Carleman's theorem show that Borel summation produces such a best possible sum of the series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Watson's theorem gives conditions for a function to be the Borel sum of its asymptotic series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] for all *z* in the region (for some positive constant *C*).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Then Watson's theorem says that in this region *f* is given by the Borel sum of its asymptotic series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] More precisely, the series for the Borel transform converges in a neighborhood of the origin, and can be analytically continued to the positive real axis, and the integral defining the Borel sum converges to *f*(*z*) for *z* in the region above.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Carleman's theorem shows that a function is uniquely determined by an asymptotic series in a sector provided the errors in the finite order approximations do not grow too fast.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] More precisely it states that if *f* is analytic in the interior of the sector |*z*| < *C*, Re(*z*) > 0 and |*f*(*z*)| < |*b**n**z*|*n* in this region for all *n*, then *f* is zero provided that the series 1/*b*0 + 1/*b*1 + ... diverges.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Carleman's theorem gives a summation method for any asymptotic series whose terms do not grow too fast, as the sum can be defined to be the unique function with this asymptotic series in a suitable sector if it exists.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Borel summation is slightly weaker than special case of this when *b**n* =*cn* for some constant *c*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] More generally one can define summation methods slightly stronger than Borel's by taking the numbers *b**n* to be slightly larger, for example *b**n* = *cn*log *n* or *b**n* =*cn*log *n* log log *n*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] In practice this generalization is of little use, as there are almost no natural examples of series summable by this method that cannot also be summed by Borel's method.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The function *f*(*z*) = exp(–1/*z*) has the asymptotic series 0 + 0*z* + ... with an error bound of the form above in the region |arg(*z*)| < *θ* for any *θ* < π/2, but is not given by the Borel sum of its asymptotic series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] This shows that the number π/2 in Watson's theorem cannot be replaced by any smaller number (unless the bound on the error is made smaller).
