[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The following example extends on that given in (Hardy 1992, 8.5).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Via the convergence theorem along chords, the Borel integral converges for all *z* ≤ 2 (the integral diverges for *z* > 2).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] holds only for *z* < 1, and so the weak Borel sum converges on this smaller domain.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] If a formal series *A*(*z*) is Borel summable at *z*0 ∈ **C**, then it is also Borel summable at all points on the chord O*z*0 connecting *z*0 to the origin.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] An immediate consequence is that the domain of convergence of the Borel sum is a star domain in **C**.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] More can be said about the domain of convergence of the Borel sum, than that it is a star domain, which is referred to as the Borel polygon, and is determined by the singularities of the series *A*(*z*).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Suppose that *A*(*z*) has strictly positive radius of convergence, so that it is analytic in a non-trivial region containing the origin, and let *S**A* denote the set of singularities of *A*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] This means that *P* ∈ *S**A* if and only if *A* can be continued analytically along the open chord from 0 to *P*, but not to *P* itself.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] For *P* ∈ *SA*, let *LP* denote the line passing through *P* which is perpendicular to the chord *OP*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] the set of points which lie on the same side of *LP* as the origin.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] An alternative definition was used by Borel and Phragmén (Sansone & Gerretsen 1960, 8.3).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Let $S\subset \mathbb {C}$ denote the largest star domain on which there is an analytic extension of *A*, then $\Pi _{A}$ is the largest subset of S such that for all $P\in \Pi _{A}$ the interior of the circle with radius *OP* is contained in S .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Referring to the set $\Pi _{A}$ as a polygon is something of a misnomer, since the set need not be polygonal at all; if, however, *A*(*z*) has only finitely many singularities then $\Pi _{A}$ will in fact be a polygon.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The following theorem, due to Borel and Phragmén provides convergence criteria for Borel summation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Note that (**B**) summability for $z\in \partial \Pi _{A}$ depends on the nature of the point.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Seen as a function on **C**, *A*(*z*) has singularities at *SA* = {*ω**i* : *i* = 1, ..., *m*}, and consequently the Borel polygon $\Pi _{A}$ is given by the regular *m*-gon centred at the origin, and such that 1 ∈ **C** is a midpoint of an edge.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] converges for all $|z|<1$ (for instance, by the comparison test with the geometric series).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] It can however be shown that *A* does not converge for any point *z* ∈ **C** such that *z*2*n* = 1 for some *n*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Since the set of such *z* is dense in the unit circle, there can be no analytic extension of *A* outside of *B*(0,1).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Subsequently, the largest star domain to which *A* can be analytically extended is *S* = *B*(0,1) from which (via the second definition) one obtains $\Pi _{A}=B(0,1)$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] In particular one sees that the Borel polygon is not polygonal.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] A Tauberian theorem provides conditions under which convergence of one summation method implies convergence under another method.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] The principal Tauberian theorem for Borel summation provides conditions under which the weak Borel method implies convergence of the series.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Borel summation finds application in perturbation expansions in quantum field theory.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] In particular in 2-dimensional Euclidean field theory the Schwinger functions can often be recovered from their perturbation series using Borel summation (Glimm & Jaffe 1987, p.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Some of the singularities of the Borel transform are related to instantons and renormalons in quantum field theory (Weinberg 2005, 20.7).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] Borel summation requires that the coefficients do not grow too fast: more precisely, *a**n* has to be bounded by *n*!*C**n*+1 for some *C*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] There is a variation of Borel summation that replaces factorials *n*! with (*kn*)! for some positive integer *k*, which allows the summation of some series with *a**n* bounded by (*kn*)!*C**n*+1 for some *C*.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] This generalization is given by Mittag-Leffler summation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/borel-summation] In the most general case, Borel summation is generalized by Nachbin resummation, which can be used when the bounding function is of some general type (psi-type), instead of being exponential type.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] where f is a twice-differentiable function, M is a large number, and the endpoints a and b may be infinite.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] This technique was originally presented in the book by Laplace (1774).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] In Bayesian statistics, Laplace's approximation can refer to either approximating the posterior normalizing constant with Laplace's method or approximating the posterior distribution with a Gaussian centered at the maximum a posteriori estimate.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Laplace approximations are used in the integrated nested Laplace approximations method for fast approximations of Bayesian inference.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Let the function $f(x)$ have a unique global maximum at $x_{0}$ . $M>0$ is a constant here.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Then, $x_{0}$ is the global maximum of g and h as well.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] As *M* increases, the ratio for h will grow exponentially, while the ratio for g does not change.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Thus, significant contributions to the integral of this function will come only from points x in a neighborhood of $x_{0}$ , which can then be estimated.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] To state and motivate the method, one must make several assumptions.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] It is assumed that $x_{0}$ is not an endpoint of the interval of integration and that the values $f(x)$ cannot be very close to $f(x_{0})$ unless x is close to $x_{0}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Since f has a global maximum at $x_{0}$ , and $x_{0}$ is not an endpoint, it is a stationary point, i.e. $f'(x_{0})=0$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Then, just one more step is needed to get a Gaussian distribution.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] If $f''(x_{0})<0$ this latter integral becomes a Gaussian integral if we replace the limits of integration by $-\infty$ and $+\infty$ ; when M is large this creates only a small error because the exponential decays very fast away from $x_{0}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] A generalization of this method and extension to arbitrary precision is provided by the book Fog (2008).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Remember $f''(x_{0})<0$ so we can take the square root of its negation.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Note that this proof works also when $a=-\infty$ or $b=\infty$ (or both).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Lastly, by our assumptions (assuming $a,b$ are finite) there exists an $\eta >0$ such that if $|x-x_{0}|\geq \delta$ , then $f(x)\leq f(x_{0})-\eta$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] And combining this with the lower bound gives the result.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Note that the above proof obviously fails when $a=-\infty$ or $b=\infty$ (or both).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] To deal with these cases, we need some extra assumptions.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] and that the number $\eta$ as above exists (note that this must be an assumption in the case when the interval $[a,b]$ is infinite).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] The rest of the proof (the analysis of the interesting term) proceeds as above.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] The given condition in the infinite interval case is, as said above, sufficient but not necessary.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] However, the condition is fulfilled in many, if not in most, applications: the condition simply says that the integral we are studying must be well-defined (not infinite) and that the maximum of the function at $x_{0}$ must be a "true" maximum (the number $\eta >0$ must exist).
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] The "approximation" in this method is related to the relative error and not the absolute error.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Now, let us separate this integral into two parts: $y\in [-D_{y},D_{y}]$ region and the rest.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] From this equation you will find that the terms higher than second derivative in this Taylor expansion is suppressed as the order of ${\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {M}}}$ so that $\exp(M(f(x)-f(x_{0})))$ will get closer to the Gaussian function as shown in figure.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Because we do the comparison in y-space, y is fixed in $y\in [-D_{y},D_{y}]$ which will cause $x\in [-sD_{y},sD_{y}]$ ; however, s is inversely proportional to ${\sqrt {M}}$ , the chosen region of x will be smaller when M is increased.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Relying on the 3rd concept, even if we choose a very large *Dy*, *sDy* will finally be a very small number when M is increased to a huge number.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Then, how can we guarantee the integral of the rest will tend to 0 when M is large enough?
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] The basic idea is to find a function $m(x)$ such that $m(x)\geq f(x)$ and the integral of $e^{Mm(x)}$ will tend to zero when M grows.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Because the exponential function of $Mm(x)$ will be always larger than zero as long as $m(x)$ is a real number, and this exponential function is proportional to $m(x),$ the integral of $e^{Mf(x)}$ will tend to zero.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] If the interval of the integration of this method is finite, we will find that no matter $f(x)$ is continue in the rest region, it will be always smaller than $m(x)$ shown above when M is large enough.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] By the way, it will be proved later that the integral of $e^{Mm(x)}$ will tend to zero when M is large enough.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] If the interval of the integration of this method is infinite, $m(x)$ and $f(x)$ might always cross to each other.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] If so, we cannot guarantee that the integral of $e^{Mf(x)}$ will tend to zero finally.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/laplace-s-method] Therefore, we need to require that $\int _{d}^{\infty }e^{Mf(x)}dx$ can converge for the infinite interval case.
