[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] An early example of the dominant balance method is the Newton polygon method.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] Newton developed this method to find an explicit approximation for an algebraic function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] Newton expressed the function as proportional to the independent variable raised to a power, retained only the lowest-degree polynomial terms (dominant terms), and solved this simplified reduced equation to obtain an approximate solution.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] Dominant balance has a broad range of applications, solving differential equations arising in fluid mechanics, plasma physics, turbulence, combustion, nonlinear optics, geophysical fluid dynamics, and neuroscience.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The functions ${\textstyle f(z)}$ and $g(z)$ of parameter or independent variable ${\textstyle z}$ and the quotient ${\textstyle f(z)/g(z)}$ have limits as ${\textstyle z}$ approaches the limit ${\textstyle L}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The function ${\textstyle f(z)}$ is *much less than* ${\textstyle g(z)}$ as ${\textstyle z}$ approaches ${\textstyle L}$ , written as ${\textstyle f(z)\ll g(z)\ (z\to L)}$ , if the limit of the quotient ${\textstyle f(z)/g(z)}$ is zero as ${\textstyle z}$ approaches ${\textstyle L}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The function ${\textstyle f(z)}$ is *equivalent* to ${\textstyle g(z)}$ as ${\textstyle z}$ approaches ${\textstyle L}$ , written as ${\textstyle f(z)\sim g(z)\ (z\to L)}$ , if the limit of the quotient ${\textstyle f(z)/g(z)}$ is 1 as ${\textstyle z}$ approaches ${\textstyle L}$ .
