[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] In some cases, the reduced equation has coefficients containing a parameter ${\textstyle \epsilon }$ , but the parameter's exponent is different for the 2 terms.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] In this case, the reduced equation requires a *scale transformation* ${\textstyle z=\epsilon ^{\lambda }{\tilde {z}}}$ of the variable ${\textstyle z}$ using scaling exponent ${\textstyle \lambda }$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The dominant balance method selects a scaling exponent ${\textstyle \lambda }$ to generate transformed terms, each transformed term now containing the parameter with the same exponent.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] Distinct pairs of terms and scaling transformations lead to distinct simplified equations called *distinguished limits*, and each equation may lead to a distinct solution.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The Kruskal-Newton diagram facilitates identifying the required scale transformation needed for dominant balance of algebraic and differential equations.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] For differential equation solutions containing an irregular singularity, the *leading behavior* is the first term of an asymptotic series solution that remains when the independent variable ${\textstyle z}$ approaches an irregular singularity ${\textstyle L}$ .
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The *controlling factor* is the fastest changing part of the leading behavior.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The input is the set of equation terms and the limit L.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The output is the set of approximate solutions.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] For each pair of distinct equation terms ${\textstyle T_{i}(s),T_{j}(s)}$ the algorithm applies a scale transformation if needed, balances the selected terms by finding a function that solves the reduced equation and then determines if this function is consistent.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] If the function balances the terms and is consistent, the algorithm adds the function to the set of approximate solutions, otherwise the algorithm rejects the function.
[src:asymptotic-analysis/method-of-dominant-balance] The process is repeated for each pair of distinct equation terms.
